  <slide>
    <title>World Wide Web Consortium</title>
    <contents>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="http://www.w3.org/" target="_specification">World Wide Web Consortium (W3C)</a></li>
        <li>Over 400 member organizations representing industry, governments and academic interests.</li>
        <li>Develop open and royality free standards:
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/html52/">Hypertext Markup Language (HTML) Specifications</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/css">Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) Specifications</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/PNG/">Portable Network Graphics (PNG) Specifications</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/SVG/">Scallable Vector Graphics (SVG) Specifications</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/MATHML/">Mathematical Markup Language (MathML) Specifications</a></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Interopability through at least 2 indepdent implementations</li>
        <li>Automated testing of technologies using the speficications.</li>
      </ul>

      <iframe src="https://www.w3.org" width="99%" height="600px" title="World Wide Web Home page"></iframe>
    </contents>
  </slide>


  <slide>
    <title>Interoperability</title>
    <contents>
      <ul>
        <li>Write once and use on a wide variety of devices.</li>
        <li>No proprietary technologies or royalties for use.</li>
        <li>W3C requires two independent implementations before a specification can be considered a recommendation.</li>
        <li>In the early days of the web the browser wars between Internet Explorer and Netscape Navigator highlighted the need for standards based web design.</li>
      </ul>
    </contents>
  </slide>


  <slide>
    <title>Interoperability for Accessibility</title>
    <contents>
      <h2>Old Model for Accessibility</h2>

      <p>If it worked with some version of the JAWS screen reader and a particular version of Microsoft Internet Explorer, a website was consideed accessible.</p>

      <h2>New Model for Accessibility</h2>

      <h3>Screen Readers</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>MacOS and VocieOver: Safari, Chrome, Firefox</li>
        <li>iOS and VocieOver: Safari</li>
        <li>Android and TalkBack: chrome</li>
        <li>Windows 10 and NVDA: Chrome and Firefox</li>
        <li>Windows 10 and JAWS: Chrome and Firefox</li>
        <li>Windows 10 and Narrator: Chrome and Firefox</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Magnifiers and High Contrast</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>MacOS and Zoom: Safari, Chrome, Firefox</li>
        <li>iOS and Zoom: Safari</li>
        <li>Android and Magnifer: chrome</li>
        <li>Windows 10 and Magnifier: Chrome and Firefox</li>
        <li>Windows 10 and Zoomtext: Chrome and Firefox</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Other Common Assistive Technologies</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Voice Recognition: Dragon Naturally Speaking, MacOS Speech Recognition</li>
        <li>Learning Disabilities: Kurzweil 3000, Read and Write Gold</li>
      </ul>

    </contents>
  </slide>

